  <span id="freeText5189859353579649338" style="display:none"><strong>With his characteristic raw and minimalist style, Charles Bukowski takes us on a walk through his side of town in <em>Hot Water Music</em>.Â  He gives us little vignettes of depravity and lasciviousness, bite sized pieces of what is both beautiful and grotesque.</strong><br /><br />The stories in <em>Hot Water Music</em> dash around the worst parts of town â a motel room stinking of sick, a decrepit apartment housing a perpetually arguing couple, a bar tended by a skeleton â and depict the darkest parts of human existence.Â  Bukowski talks simply and profoundly about the underbelly of the working class without raising judgement.Â <br /><br />In the way he writes about sex, relationships, writing, and inebriation, Bukowski sets the bar for irreverent art â his work inhabits the basest part of the mind and the most extreme absurdity of the everyday.</span>
