        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3195470630" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9051854910937049330"><br/>I&apos;d already read most of his novels by the time I read this, but Hot Water Music was the first of his short story volumes that I encountered. Just grabbing the book from my bookshelf and having a glance at the contents page, I forgot how many stories were in it and as I flipped through some of the book, I remembered that most stories are only a few pages long and so perfect for getting through a few each reading session. The content of these stories are quite similar to what you&apos;d find in his no</span>
  <span id="freeText9051854910937049330" style="display:none"><br />I'd already read most of his novels by the time I read this, but Hot Water Music was the first of his short story volumes that I encountered. Just grabbing the book from my bookshelf and having a glance at the contents page, I forgot how many stories were in it and as I flipped through some of the book, I remembered that most stories are only a few pages long and so perfect for getting through a few each reading session. The content of these stories are quite similar to what you'd find in his novels- drinking bouts, going to dog and horse races, escapades with various rough and ready women, hangovers and on the other hand, listening to classical music, talking about literature, mulling over life when feeling down...so they are pretty varied really, although always raw and uncompromising like his novels. <br />Some of the stories feature his alter ego, Henry Chinaski, whereas others have totally random characters, where you get a quick burst of some young couple arguing or some odd debauched scenario that plays out over just a few pages, but paints the picture it needs to perfectly before you are plunged into the next slice of depravity...a good place to start for new Bukowski readers, not that there's a bad place to start in my opinion. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9051854910937049330" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


